'''Kārlis Zirnis''' (born 2 November 1977) is a [[Latvia]]n retired [[ice hockey]] player and current assistant coach for the [[Alaska Nanooks men's ice hockey]] team.

==Career==
Zirnis played [[junior hockey]] in Latvia before moving to the [[United States]], where he played for the [[Gaylord Grizzlies]] in the [[North American Hockey League]] in the 1997–98 season.  From 1999 through 2003, he played [[college hockey]] for the [[Alabama–Huntsville Chargers men's ice hockey|Alabama–Huntsville Chargers]].  Zirnis led the team in scoring during his [[2000–01 Alabama–Huntsville Chargers men's ice hockey season|sophomore]] and [[2001–02 Alabama–Huntsville Chargers men's ice hockey season|junior]] seasons in Huntsville.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alabama-Huntsville Men – 2000–2001 Team Statistics |url=http://collegehockeystats.net/0001/teamstats/alhm |website=collegehockeystats.net |accessdate=28 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YsD4l2vF?url=http://collegehockeystats.net/0001/teamstats/alhm |archivedate=28 May 2015 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alabama-Huntsville Chargers (Men) 2001–2002 Team Statistics |url=http://collegehockeystats.net/0102/teamstats/alhm |website=collegehockeystats.net |accessdate=28 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YsD5wRIY?url=http://collegehockeystats.net/0102/teamstats/alhm |archivedate=28 May 2015 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>  After graduating, he played 5 seasons in the [[Central Hockey League]] with the [[Amarillo Gorillas]], [[Colorado Eagles]], and the [[Bossier-Shreveport Mudbugs]].  Zirnis finished his playing career with the [[Huntsville Havoc]] of the [[Southern Professional Hockey League]], where he was the team's captain in the 2008–09 season, and retired after 1 game of the 2009–10 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Karlis Zirnis |url=http://www.eliteprospects.com/player.php?player=14634&lang=en |website=Elite Prospects |accessdate=28 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YsD7Bd6v?url=http://www.eliteprospects.com/player.php?player=14634 |archivedate=28 May 2015 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>

After retiring from playing, Zirnis was a [[Scout (sport)|scout]] for the NAHL's [[Amarillo Bulls]] and an assistant coach for the TPH Thunder [[Minor ice hockey#United States|midget hockey]] organization.  He was named [[Ted Nolan]]'s assistant for the [[Latvia men's national ice hockey team|Latvian national team]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lhf.lv/14112013-nolans_turpmak_apvienos_darbus_latvijas_i|title=Nolans turpmāk apvienos darbus Latvijas izlasē un Bufalo "Sabres"|author= LHF |publisher=lhf.lv|date=2013-11-14|accessdate=2014-05-03|language=Latvian}}</ref> before the [[2013 IIHF World Championship]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reports.iihf.hockey/Hydra/352/IHM3520LAT_33_2_0.pdf|title=TEAM ROSTER|author=IIHF|publisher=iihf.com|date=2013-05-05|accessdate=2014-05-03}}</ref> and also coached in the [[2014 IIHF World Championship|2014]] and [[2015 IIHF World Championship|2015]] World Championships and the [[Ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCarter |first1=Mark |title=Ex-UAH and Havoc star Karlis Zirnis back from Olympic coaching job, scores game-winner for Legends |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/03/ex-uah_and_havoc_star_karlis_z.html |accessdate=28 May 2015 |work=[[The Huntsville Times]] |date=22 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YsDGsttt?url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/03/ex-uah_and_havoc_star_karlis_z.html |archivedate=28 May 2015 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> From 2013 to 2016, Zirnis was the head coach of the [[Nashville Junior Predators]] of the [[North American 3 Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Zirnis takes over for Howard as head coach in Nashville |url=http://na3hl.com/news/story.cfm?id=11851 |publisher=NA3HL |accessdate=28 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YsDJIgEH?url=http://na3hl.com/news/story.cfm?id=11851 |archivedate=28 May 2015 |deadurl=no |date=5 August 2014 |df= }}</ref> In 2016, Zirnis was named the first head coach of the [[Shreveport Mudbugs]] in the [[North American Hockey League]], an expansion team using the name of his former CHL team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bossierpress.com/former-mudbug-zirnis-named-head-coach-of-new-shreveport-mudbugs-nahl-team/ |title=Former Mudbug Zirnis named head coach of new Shreveport Mudbugs NAHL team |publisher=''Bossier Press-Tribune'' |date=June 2, 2016}}</ref>

In the 2017–18 NAHL season, Zirnis led the Mudbugs to the [[Robertson Cup]] championship. Following the season, he joined the [[Alaska Nanooks men's ice hockey|University of Alaska-Fairbanks hockey team]] as an assistant coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.shreveporttimes.com/story/sports/mudbugs/2018/07/12/karlis-zirnis-leaves-mudbugs-coach-ncaa-fairbanks-nahl/781386002/ |title=Karlis Zirnis leaves Mudbugs to coach in NCAA |work=[[Shreveport Times]] |date=July 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsminer.com/sports/former-mudbugs-coach-karlis-zirnis-joins-uaf-hockey-coaching-staff/article_cb47f346-8674-11e8-8bb9-cb022e6412ea.html |title=Former Mudbugs coach Karlis Zirnis joins UAF hockey coaching staff |work=[[Daily News-Miner]] |date=July 13, 2018}}</ref>

